Democracy without people's solidarity
Something has happened to democracy in the sense that the government is elected by the people, and this has happened everywhere in the world.
Somehow, people have lost faith in elections.
Voter turnout is declining in many countries; in the case of the European Parliament elections, voter turnout was so ridiculously low that the legitimacy of the election result is questionable.
Apart from voter turnout, we have become accustomed to accepting parties or candidates who receive 25% of the votes as "winners."
From Holland through Finland to Argentina and Japan, majority governments are formed on the basis of minorities.
Even the apparent exceptions do not prove the opposite.
Only a few American presidents have been elected by more than 10% of the electorate. In fact, half of the voters in the USA have not even registered to participate in the election; of those who have registered, half do not vote; of those who vote, less than half vote for the election winner.
Even Tony Blair's "dam-breaking" majority in the UK House of Commons is on shaky ground: The Labour Party received only slightly over 40% of the votes in the last election in 2002, with a voter turnout of 60%.
Accordingly, only 24% of the total electorate supported Blair's party.
In most countries, the situation with elections looks very different now than it did twenty, or even fifty, years ago.
What has happened?
A possible answer is that voters distrust the political parties.
The electoral democracy functions in most countries through the mediation of organizations that put forward candidates who stand for specific packages of political options, for a "manifesto" or a "platform."
For a number of reasons, this long-established practice no longer functions.
Ideological party programs have lost their power; voters no longer accept the packages put together by the parties, they want to select and choose things for themselves.
Moreover, political parties have become machines composed of tightly organized inner circles of insiders.
The paradox here is that the parties have become even more clique-like with the loss of their specific ideological orientation.
It is more important to belong to them than to share their specific beliefs.
Such developments have alienated the parties from the voter.
Because most people no longer want to belong to any particular party, only a minority plays the party game anymore.
Thus, public suspicion of political parties grows not least because, as in professional sports, it is expensive to participate.
If the costs are borne by the taxpayer, this is resented.
Yet without financial support from the state, parties would have to obtain money through channels that are often questionable, if not even illegal.
Many of the major political scandals of the last decades began with the financing of parties and their candidates.
Other indicators - such as the明显 decline in memberships - confirm that the parties have become unpopular.
Nevertheless, parties are indispensable for a democracy based on elections.
The result is an obvious separation between the visible political actors and the electorate.
Because the parties are active in parliaments, the effects of this separation concern one of the key institutions of democracy.
People no longer believe that the parliaments represent them and thus are equipped with the necessary legitimacy to make decisions on their behalf.
At this point, a second, quite independent development comes into play.
People today are more impatient than ever before.
As consumers, they are accustomed to immediate satisfaction.
Yet they must wait as voters before they can feel the effects of the election results they have cast at the ballot box.
Sometimes they never see the desired results.
Democracy needs time not only for elections, but also for discussions and careful consideration.
The consumer as a voter, however, will not accept this and therefore turns away.
There are alternatives. Yet each has its own problems as a democratic solution.
"Direct Action" through demonstrations became a regular and often effective event.
For less mobile people, it could be replaced by the possibility of expressing their opinion electronically; this ranges from internet forums to electronic messages to political leaders.
Then there are the non-governmental organizations. They often have undemocratic internal structures, yet they still seem to be more closely connected to the citizens.
In addition, there is of course the possibility of completely disengaging and leaving politics to the experts in order to focus on other aspects of life.
The latter undoubtedly poses the greatest risks, as it fosters the creeping authoritarianism that is a hallmark of our time.
But the other signs of the separation between politics and citizens also contribute to a rather uncertain situation, because no one can anymore say how representative the prevailing views are.
Some would like to untangle the knot by increasing direct democracy.
But a lasting connection between leaders and the led cannot be established by reducing public discussion to simple voting alternatives.
There would be much more to be said in favor of holding on to the classical institutions of parliamentary democracy and trying to reconnect them more closely with the citizenry.
After all, unpopular parties and declining voter participation could turn out to be only a temporary phenomenon.
New parties could emerge and inject more life into elections and representative governments.
But this is probably not enough to restore the general legitimacy that elected governments have lost.
Therefore, the primary concern of all those who value constitutional freedom must be to rethink democracy and its institutions.
